properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Thomson River to Cowwarr Weir.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT U/S COWWARR WEIR. 

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT WANDOCKA FROM LATE THURSDAY MORNING. 

Rainfall during Wednesday and overnight into Thursday across the Thomson River catchment has resulted in some strong river level rises. Further rainfall is forecast across the Thomson River catchment for the remainder of Thursday. 

Moderate flooding is occurring at U/S Cowwarr Weir after a moderate peak early Thursday morning. Minor flooding may develop along the Thomson River at Wandocka from late Thursday morning. 

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

Thomson River to Cowwarr Weir: 
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Thomson River at Cowwarr Weir. 

The Thomson River at Cooper Ck is currently at 1.98 metres and steady. The Thomson River at Cooper Ck is expected to peak near 2.00 metres late Thursday morning (below the minor flood level of 2.30 m). 

The Thomson River U/S Cowwarr Weir peaked around 4.70 metres (moderate flood peak) early Thursday morning and is currently at 4.65 metres and slowly falling. The Thomson River U/S Cowwarr Weir may fall below the moderate flood level (4.50 m) early Thursday afternoon.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is possible in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying roads and bridges may be cut off by flood water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/11/2023 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Genoa River.

MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE IN THE GENOA RIVER

Minor flooding is likely to develop along the Cann River from Thursday afternoon, with moderate flooding possible late Thursday. Moderate flooding is occurring along the Genoa River. A major flood peak is possible on the Genoa River. With forecast rainfall, further rises to the moderate flood level are possible in the Cann and Genoa rivers late Thursday.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Thursday, rainfall totals of 100-150 mm were recorded across the Cann, Genoa and Bemm River catchments, with widespread totals of 10-40mm falling since 9:00am today. Widespread rainfall totals of 30-60mm are forecast across East Gippsland during the remainder of Thursday.

Genoa River:
Major flooding is possible along the Genoa River.

The Genoa River at The Gorge is currently at 3.04 metres and steady, with moderate flooding The Genoa River at The Gorge is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (2.90 m) for the remainder of Thursday. The river may peak around the major flood level overnight Thursday into Friday.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Road access along Mallacoota-Genoa Road will be cut across the floodway at Mangan Lake.
  • River-fronting portions of properties are potentially inundated including outlying structures such as sheds and tanks.
  • Gipsy Point public car park and rear portions of selected properties impacted, no direct building impact is observed.
  • The water will extend widely across the base of the valley.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Bemm River and Bemm River community.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Thursday, rainfall totals of 100-150 mm were recorded across the Cann, Genoa and Bemm River catchments. Widespread rainfall totals of 40-80mm are forecast across East Gippsland during the remainder of Thursday.

Bemm River:

River rises are occurring in the Bemm River catchment.

Predictive modelling indicates, flooding could be similar to impacts seen during the  April 2022 floods.
Flooding is expected to peak over the next 24 hours.

Access to the Bemm River community will be cut, when major flooding starts to occur.

Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Significant inundation of the Sydenham Inlet Road occurs, well over 0.3 of a metre (300 mm), and up to 1.6 metre at its lowest point.
  • Numerous breakouts over the left bank of  Bemm River, flowing eastward into the floodplain.
  • A large area of floodplain flooding will occur over the right bank, between Bemm River and Sydenham Parade. It's not expected for buildings to be impacted from direct flooding, isolation may occur for any properties or vehicles eastward of Cosy Nook Flats.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/11/2023 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.
